max-height: 261px;"><div class="textElement">  Name                Size                      Bytes  Class     Attributes

      data              128x128x400x3            19660800  uint8
      frame_rate          1x1                           8  double
      pixel_size          1x1                           8  double
      xplor_folder        1x29                         58  char                </div></div></div></div></div><h2  class = 'S2'><span>Start XPLOR and Enter Header Information</span></h2><div  class = 'S1'><span>Simply type:</span></div><div class="CodeBlock"><div class="inlineWrapper outputs"><div  class = 'S7'><span style="white-space: pre;"><span>xplor </span><span style="color: rgb(160, 32, 240);">data</span></span></div><div  class = 'S6'><div class="inlineElement eoOutputWrapper embeddedOutputsFigure" uid="F4A96F9A" contenteditable="false" data-testid="output_1" style="width: 1550.02px;"><div class="figureElement"><img class="figureImage figureContainingNode" src="data:image/png;base64," style="width: 560px;"></div></div></div></div></div><div  class = 'S8'><span>Enter the header information as follows:</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>The scale values are interpreted in the base Matlab workspace:</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>XPLOR will remember these values: you will not need to enter them the next time!</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>Now press </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>ok</span><span>.</span></div><h2  class = 'S2'><span>XPLOR Main Window</span></h2><div  class = 'S1'><span>The following two windows appear. </span></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>The first is the XPLOR main window:</span></div><ul  class = 'S9'><li  class = 'S10'><span>on the left, its control parts (which can be hidden with the </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>&gt;&gt; Controls</span><span> button) </span></li><li  class = 'S10'><span>on the right, its display; here XPLOR chose to show dimensions </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>x</span><span> and </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>y</span><span> in a spatial display, and to filter the other the </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>time</span><span> and </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>trial</span><span> dimensions.</span></li></ul><div  class = 'S1'><span>The second window displays lists to control the </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>time</span><span> and </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>trial</span><span> filters.</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," width = "1007" height = "493" alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span></span></div><h2  class = 'S2'><span>Linked Windows</span></h2><div  class = 'S1'><span>In addition to this spatial display, let us show a temporal display from the context menu that appears when clicking </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>time</span><span>.</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>In this new window, </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>time</span><span> is shown, while </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>x</span><span>, </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>y</span><span> and </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>trial</span><span> are filtered (note that </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>x</span><span> and </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>y</span><span> are filtered together by a single 2D filter, which we will manipulate soon).</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>Notice how the two windows are linked together. </span><span style=' font-weight: bold;'>Cross-window controls</span><span> is a first </span><span style=' font-weight: bold;'>core feature</span><span> of XPLOR: click any point in the image or drag the cross to see its signal in the time courses display, and reciprocally click any time or drag the vertical cursor in the time courses display to see the frame at that time in the image display.</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>To avoid saturations, adjust the clipping range: there are many options to control it, here are a few advices:</span></div><ul  class = 'S9'><li  class = 'S10'><span>Use the </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>Auto-Clip</span><span> feature that automatically adjust the clipping range: it is accessible in the </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>Clipping</span><span> menu but also by by double-clicking on the small black&amp;white button in the top-right corner </span><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img><span>. </span></li><li  class = 'S10'><span>If you want auto-clipping to occur whenever the displayed data changes select in the menu </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>Span &gt; Local, Adjust to Current View</span><span>.</span></li><li  class = 'S10'><span>Clip can be further adjusted by clicking on the black&amp;white button </span><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img><span>, holding the button mouse and moving the mouse horizontally to adjust the lower bound, vertically to adjust the upper bounds (their values are displayed bottom-left of the figure). You can also use the + and - minus buttons to adjust the scale </span><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAA8AAAAfCAIAAAC3YgCGAAAAdklEQVR4AWP4QApgACpeSzSAqn5IBACaObxUP1gYaVx7AM3nOH1JrGqgOgZkELkQbgPFZkNMItYlcHsxGThdgqkUKIJQDWQRA0DphHhAumpi3ABRM7xSLIHYwSqNJggMFjqHCSI/IGUFlFSF5kSsXPq4m8iEBQDadHo/3kn0CwAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==" alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img><span>.</span></li></ul><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>In the screenshot below (note that you can also change the image color map):</span></div><ul  class = 'S9'><li  class = 'S10'><span>the cross selects a pixel belonging to a neuron -&gt; its signal appears in the second window, we see peaks when the neuron is active</span></li><li  class = 'S10'><span>the vertical bar selects a peak time -&gt; the frame at this time appears in the first window and shows this neuron particularly bright.</span></li></ul><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><h2  class = 'S2'><span>Regions of Interest, Zooming</span></h2><div  class = 'S1'><span>In general, XPLOR relies on so-called </span><span style=' font-style: italic;'>filter</span><span> objects that define what is being displayed, and we saw how the cross controls so-called </span><span style=' font-style: italic;'>point filters</span><span>. Follow now the screenshots to have each window control </span><span style=' font-style: italic;'>selection filters</span><span> that define </span><span style=' font-weight: bold;'>regions of interest (ROI)</span><span> over which to average individual pixels' signals or individual frames.</span></div><h3  class = 'S11'><span>1) Spatial ROI</span></h3><div  class = 'S1'><span>We want to define in the image display spatial ROIs whose time courses will be shown in the other window</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>Right-click and drag in the window to make circle selections. Their time courses appear in the second window.</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>To facilitate the selection of ROIs, it will help to </span><span style=' font-weight: bold;'>zoom</span><span> in the image. There are 3 ways to zoom in and out:</span></div><ul  class = 'S9'><li  class = 'S10'><span>click and drag inside the graph with the left button to zoom in; double-click to reset zoom</span></li><li  class = 'S10'><span>use the scroll wheel</span></li><li  class = 'S10'><span>first click the </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>x</span><span> and </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>y</span><span> labels to make zooming sliders appear to the top and to the right of the display; click and drag their edges to control the zoom limits; double-click on the slider to reset zoom</span></li></ul><div  class = 'S1'><span>Note also that you can select not only circles but also ellipses: make a click with the mouse left button while you keep the right button pressed: the ellipse main axis is now fixed and you can control its width by continuing to drag.</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>You can also use other drawing shapes:</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>On the time courses side, note that you can color each trace by the color of its corresponding ROI in the context menu that appears when right-clicking the </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>x-y ROI</span><span> dimension label. It can also improve the display to center each signal vertically on its mean value.</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>We reached here so far:</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span></span></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>Now the time courses of these regions of interest appear in the other window: all the peaks correspond to periods of time where the neurons are particularly active.</span></div><h3  class = 'S11'><span>2) Temporal ROI</span></h3><div  class = 'S1'><span>Symetrically temporal selections can be made in the time courses display.</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>We first trace a large selection (again, by right-click and dragging the mouse inside the graph: result is the blue rectangle below). The image window now shows the average movie image.</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>It would be possible to define more than one temporal selections, for example at times of neuronal activity. We then obtain multiple images and a new </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>time ROI</span><span> dimension appears in the first window.</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>Now notice that the </span><span style=' font-weight: bold;'>dimensions can be moved around</span><span>, this is</span><span style=' font-weight: bold;'> </span><span>a core feature of XPLOR to ease</span><span style=' font-weight: bold;'> "looking at data from different perspectives"!</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>Click and drag the new </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>time ROI</span><span> dimension label to move it above the graph.</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>But for now we will remain with a single time selection. For this we can select in the second window:</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," width = "257" height = "181" alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img><span>.</span></div><h2  class = 'S2'><span>More on filters, list filters</span></h2><div  class = 'S1'><span>Click on a </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>filter trial</span><span> box to see the </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>trials</span><span> filtering list (you can close the </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>time</span><span> filtering list as it will not be used).</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><img class = "imageNode" src = "data:image/png;base64," alt = "" style = "vertical-align: baseline"></img></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>If we select the 3 trials, all the image and time courses are "multiplied" by 3!     %% XPLOR demo on Two-Photon Calcium Imaging of a Neuronal Population
    % Data from I-Wen Chen and Emiliano Ronzitti from Prof. Valentina Emiliani's
    % lab in the Vision Institute.
    %
    % Thomas Deneux, 17/04/2020
    %% Load Data
    % The data consists of 3 movies of 400 frames with 128x128 pixels.

    xplor_folder = fileparts(which('xplor'));
    cd(xplor_folder)
    cd 'demo data'
    load neuron_movies
    whos
    %% Start XPLOR and Enter Header Information
    % Simply type:

    xplor data
    %%
    % Enter the header information as follows:
    %
    %
    %
    % The scale values are interpreted in the base Matlab workspace:
    %
    %
    %
    % XPLOR will remember these values: you will not need to enter them the next
    % time!
    %
    % Now press |ok|.
    %% XPLOR Main Window
    % The following two windows appear.
    %
    % The first is the XPLOR main window:
    %%
    % * on the left, its control parts (which can be hidden with the |>> Controls|
    % button)
    % * on the right, its display; here XPLOR chose to show dimensions |x| and |y|
    % in a spatial display, and to filter the other the |time| and |trial| dimensions.
    %%
    % The second window displays lists to control the |time| and |trial| filters.
    %
    %
    %
    %
    %% Linked Windows
    % In addition to this spatial display, let us show a temporal display from the
    % context menu that appears when clicking |time|.
    %
    %
    %
    % In this new window, |time| is shown, while |x|, |y| and |trial| are filtered
    % (note that |x| and |y| are filtered together by a single 2D filter, which we
    % will manipulate soon).
    %
    %
    %
    % Notice how the two windows are linked together. *Cross-window controls* is
    % a first *core feature* of XPLOR: click any point in the image or drag the cross
    % to see its signal in the time courses display, and reciprocally click any time
    % or drag the vertical cursor in the time courses display to see the frame at
    % that time in the image display.
    %
    % To avoid saturations, adjust the clipping range: there are many options to
    % control it, here are a few advices:
    %%
    % * Use the |Auto-Clip| feature that automatically adjust the clipping range:
    % it is accessible in the |Clipping| menu but also by by double-clicking on the
    % small black&white button in the top-right corner .
    % * If you want auto-clipping to occur whenever the displayed data changes select
    % in the menu |Span > Local, Adjust to Current View|.
    % * Clip can be further adjusted by clicking on the black&white button , holding
    % the button mouse and moving the mouse horizontally to adjust the lower bound,
    % vertically to adjust the upper bounds (their values are displayed bottom-left
    % of the figure). You can also use the + and - minus buttons to adjust the scale
    % .
    %%
    %
    %
    % In the screenshot below (note that you can also change the image color map):
    %%
    % * the cross selects a pixel belonging to a neuron -> its signal appears in
    % the second window, we see peaks when the neuron is active
    % * the vertical bar selects a peak time -> the frame at this time appears in
    % the first window and shows this neuron particularly bright.
    %%
    %
    %% Regions of Interest, Zooming
    % In general, XPLOR relies on so-called _filter_ objects that define what is
    % being displayed, and we saw how the cross controls so-called _point filters_.
    % Follow now the screenshots to have each window control _selection filters_ that
    % define *regions of interest (ROI)* over which to average individual pixels'
    % signals or individual frames.
    % 1) Spatial ROI
    % We want to define in the image display spatial ROIs whose time courses will
    % be shown in the other window
    %
    %
    %
    % Right-click and drag in the window to make circle selections. Their time courses
    % appear in the second window.
    %
    %
    %
    % To facilitate the selection of ROIs, it will help to *zoom* in the image.
    % There are 3 ways to zoom in and out:
    %%
    % * click and drag inside the graph with the left button to zoom in; double-click
    % to reset zoom
    % * use the scroll wheel
    % * first click the |x| and |y| labels to make zooming sliders appear to the
    % top and to the right of the display; click and drag their edges to control the
    % zoom limits; double-click on the slider to reset zoom
    %%
    % Note also that you can select not only circles but also ellipses: make a click
    % with the mouse left button while you keep the right button pressed: the ellipse
    % main axis is now fixed and you can control its width by continuing to drag.
    %
    %
    %
    % You can also use other drawing shapes:
    %
    %
    %
    % On the time courses side, note that you can color each trace by the color
    % of its corresponding ROI in the context menu that appears when right-clicking
    % the |x-y ROI| dimension label. It can also improve the display to center each
    % signal vertically on its mean value.
    %
    %
    %
    %
    %
    % We reached here so far:
    %
    %
    %
    %
    %
    % Now the time courses of these regions of interest appear in the other window:
    % all the peaks correspond to periods of time where the neurons are particularly
    % active.
    % 2) Temporal ROI
    % Symetrically temporal selections can be made in the time courses display.
    %
    %
    %
    % We first trace a large selection (again, by right-click and dragging the mouse
    % inside the graph: result is the blue rectangle below). The image window now
    % shows the average movie image.
    %
    %
    %
    % It would be possible to define more than one temporal selections, for example
    % at times of neuronal activity. We then obtain multiple images and a new |time
    % ROI| dimension appears in the first window.
    %
    %
    %
    % Now notice that the *dimensions can be moved around*, this is a core feature
    % of XPLOR to ease *"looking at data from different perspectives"!*
    %
    % Click and drag the new |time ROI| dimension label to move it above the graph.
    %
    %
    %
    %
    %
    % But for now we will remain with a single time selection. For this we can select
    % in the second window:
    %
    % .
    %% More on filters, list filters
    % Click on a |filter trial| box to see the |trials| filtering list (you can
    % close the |time| filtering list as it will not be used).
    %
    %
    %
    % If we select the 3 trials, all the image and time courses are "multiplied"
    % by 3! Reorganize the dimensions in theses displays by dragging the dimension
    % labels.
    %
    %
    %
    % The three images are the average image for each trial, and in the right window
    % we see 30 signals for 10 neurons and 3 trials.
    %
    % The first time point of the signals is lower, this is a small acquisition
    % artefact that can be hidden by slighly moving up the lower limit of a temporal
    % zoom: click the |time| dimension label to make the zooming slider appear and
    % drag sligtly its left edge.
    %
    %
    %
    % We would prefer to see the global average image rather than one image per
    % trial: right click in the list to tell that so-called "temporary selection"
    % will be groups rather than individuals.
    %
    %
    %
    % That way we created a "trial ROI", and obtained indeed an average image over
    % the 3 trials. If you want to keep the 3 individual trials in the time courses
    % display, you can remove trial filtering there.
    %
    %
    %
    % We can also re-define how filters act on ROIs: by default averaging is performed,
    % but we can use different operations, for example |max| to get the maximum value
    % of every pixel over time and trials (we have selected in the menu |Selection
    % > Stop selection control| to hide the neurons ROIs).
    %
    %
    %% Save the selection
    % Do not forget to save the neurons selections so you can load them at a later
    % time!
    %
    %
    %% Get the time courses of the selected neuron ROIs
    % Wondered about the |Developer| menu? At the present time, there are no dedicated
    % export functions, but by selecting |View object in base space| you can create
    % in Matlab base workspace a variable |V| that allows you accessing all the content
    % of this figure.
    %
    %

    V
    %%
    % In particular, |V.data| contains the original data (data + header information),
    % and |V.slice| the data displayed in the figure (data + header information),
    % after filters have been applied to the original data.

    V.slice
    disp(V.slice.header)
    y = V.slice.data;
    size(y)
    %%
    % The created |y| variable contains the time courses of the 20 selected neurons
    % and for the 3 trials.
    %
    % We can also obtain the shape definitions and pixel indices of the neuron selections
    % as follows:

    V.slicer.filters.obj.F
    V.slicer.filters.obj.F.selection(1)
    ##### SOURCE END #####
